- **Latest Version**: Mongoose v9.6.3
- **Key Config Option**: `noCursorTimeout` for cursor management.
- **CLI Commands**:
  - To install Mongoose: `npm install mongoose@latest`
  - To use `findById`: `const doc = await Model.findById(id);`
- **Code Sample**:
  ```javascript
  const mongoose = require('mongoose');
  const Schema = mongoose.Schema;

  const storySchema = new Schema({
    title: String,
    author: String,
    _id: { type: String, required: true }
  });

  const Story = mongoose.model('Story', storySchema);

  async function findStoryById(id) {
    try {
      const doc = await Story.findById(id);
      console.log(doc);
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(error);
    }
  }

  findStoryById('some-id');
  ```

search:common+errors:nestjs module missi.content:
- Ensure you have the latest version of NestJS installed globally using `npm install -g @nestjs/cli`.
- Verify your project's dependencies are up-to-date by running `npm update`.
- Check if `@nestjs/core` is listed in your `package.json` and install it with `npm install @nestjs/core`.
- Confirm that your `app.module.ts` file exists at the root of your project.
- Use `nest generate module app` to create an `AppModule` if it doesn't exist.
- Ensure your main application entry point (usually `main.ts`) correctly imports and uses `AppModule`, e.g.,:
  ```typescript
  import { NestFactory } from '@nestjs/core';
  import { AppModule } from './app.module';

  async function bootstrap() {
    const app = await NestFactory.create(AppModule);
    await app.listen(3000);
  }
  bootstrap();
  ```
- Check for any typos in your module imports and file paths.
- If using TypeScript, ensure your `tsconfig.json` is correctly configured to include all necessary files.
